Data Sources¶

This dataset comprises information from 100 machines throughout the year 2015, providing an extensive hourly time series. The dataset comprises of five data sources.

  1. Telemetry Data (PdM_telemetry.csv): For the year 2015, the dataset provides hourly average measurements of voltage, rotation, pressure, and vibration collected from 100 machines.

  2. Error (PdM_errors.csv): These errors occur while the machines are in operation but do not result in machine shutdown, and thus, they are not categorized as failures. The error date and times are rounded to the nearest hour to align with the telemetry data collection frequency

  3. Maintenance (PdM_maint.csv): If a machine component is replaced, it is recorded in this table. Component replacements occur in two situations: 1) During regular scheduled visits, technicians perform proactive maintenance by replacing the component. 2) In case of a component breakdown, technicians conduct unscheduled maintenance to replace the faulty component, which is considered a failure and captured in the Failures data. The maintenance data includes records from both 2014 and 2015 and is rounded to the nearest hour to align with the hourly telemetry data collection rate.

  4. Failures (PdM_failures.csv): Each entry in this dataset signifies the replacement of a failed component.

  5. Machines (PdM_Machines.csv): Contains the model type and age of the Machines.

def plot_machine_telemetry(machineID, start_date, end_date):
    """ Plot the telemetry data for a given machine and time period.

    Parameters
    ----------
    machineID : int
        ID of the machine to plot the telemetry data for.
    start_date : str
        Start date of the time period to plot the telemetry data for.
    end_date : str
        End date of the time period to plot the telemetry data for.

    Returns
    -------
    None
    """
    # filter the data for the given machine and time period
    start_datetime = datetime.datetime.strptime(start_date, "%Y-%m-%d")
    end_datetime = datetime.datetime.strptime(end_date, "%Y-%m-%d")
    plot_df = df_telemetry.loc[
        (df_telemetry["machineID"] == machineID)
        & (df_telemetry["datetime"] >= start_datetime)
        & (df_telemetry["datetime"] <= end_datetime)
    ]

    # create a plot for each of the telemetry variables
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=2, ncols=2, figsize=(20, 20))
    fig.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.3)
    plot_df.plot(x="datetime", y="volt", title="voltage", ax=axes[0, 0])
    plot_df.plot(x="datetime", y="rotate", title="rotate", ax=axes[0, 1])
    plot_df.plot(x="datetime", y="pressure", title="pressure", ax=axes[1, 0])
    plot_df.plot(x="datetime", y="vibration", title="vibration", ax=axes[1, 1])
    plt.show()

Plotting a shorter time period. Otherwise, difficult to see the pattern.

def plot_machine_telemetry(machineID1, machineID2, start_date, end_date):
    # filter the data for the given machines and time period
    start_datetime = datetime.datetime.strptime(start_date, "%Y-%m-%d")
    end_datetime = datetime.datetime.strptime(end_date, "%Y-%m-%d")
    plot_df1 = df_telemetry.loc[
        (df_telemetry["machineID"] == machineID1)
        & (df_telemetry["datetime"] >= start_datetime)
        & (df_telemetry["datetime"] <= end_datetime)
    ]
    plot_df2 = df_telemetry.loc[
        (df_telemetry["machineID"] == machineID2)
        & (df_telemetry["datetime"] >= start_datetime)
        & (df_telemetry["datetime"] <= end_datetime)
    ]

    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=2, ncols=2, figsize=(20, 14))
    fig.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.3)
    plot_df1.plot(
        x="datetime",
        y="volt",
        title="voltage",
        ax=axes[0, 0],
        label="Machine {}".format(machineID1),
    )
    plot_df2.plot(
        x="datetime",
        y="volt",
        title="voltage",
        ax=axes[0, 0],
        label="Machine {}".format(machineID2),
    )
    plot_df1.plot(
        x="datetime",
        y="rotate",
        title="rotate",
        ax=axes[0, 1],
        label="Machine {}".format(machineID1),
    )
    plot_df2.plot(
        x="datetime",
        y="rotate",
        title="rotate",
        ax=axes[0, 1],
        label="Machine {}".format(machineID2),
    )
    plot_df1.plot(
        x="datetime",
        y="pressure",
        title="pressure",
        ax=axes[1, 0],
        label="Machine {}".format(machineID1),
    )
    plot_df2.plot(
        x="datetime",
        y="pressure",
        title="pressure",
        ax=axes[1, 0],
        label="Machine {}".format(machineID2),
    )
    plot_df1.plot(
        x="datetime",
        y="vibration",
        title="vibration",
        ax=axes[1, 1],
        label="Machine {}".format(machineID1),
    )
    plot_df2.plot(
        x="datetime",
        y="vibration",
        title="vibration",
        ax=axes[1, 1],
        label="Machine {}".format(machineID2),
    )
    for ax in axes.flatten():
        ax.legend()
    plt.show()

# A function to plot the histogram and box plot for all telemetry values for a given machine
def plot_machine_telemetry_hist(machineID):
    """ Plot the histogram and box plot for all telemetry values for a given machine.

    Parameters
    ----------
    machineID : int
        ID of the machine to plot the telemetry data for.

    Returns
    -------
    None
    """
    # filter the data for the given machine
    plot_df = df_telemetry.loc[df_telemetry["machineID"] == machineID]

    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=4, ncols=2, figsize=(20, 20))
    fig.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.5)
    sns.distplot(plot_df["volt"], ax=axes[0, 0])
    sns.boxplot(plot_df["volt"], ax=axes[0, 1])
    sns.distplot(plot_df["rotate"], ax=axes[1, 0])
    sns.boxplot(plot_df["rotate"], ax=axes[1, 1])
    sns.distplot(plot_df["pressure"], ax=axes[2, 0])
    sns.boxplot(plot_df["pressure"], ax=axes[2, 1])
    sns.distplot(plot_df["vibration"], ax=axes[3, 0])
    sns.boxplot(plot_df["vibration"], ax=axes[3, 1])
    plt.show()

Are the telemetry variables normally distributed?¶

We apply D'Agostino and Pearson's omnibus normality test. Its based on kurtois and skewness.

In [ ]:
def normality_test(machineID):
    # filter the data for the given machine
    plot_df = df_telemetry.loc[df_telemetry["machineID"] == machineID]

    # test for normality
    for col in ["volt", "rotate", "pressure", "vibration"]:
        print(f"Normality test for {col} for machine {machineID}")
        print(normaltest(plot_df[col]))
        print("\n")


normality_test(1)

Normality test for volt for machine 1
NormaltestResult(statistic=12.119853216962973, pvalue=0.0023345722190421534)


Normality test for rotate for machine 1
NormaltestResult(statistic=35.79596132281163, pvalue=1.6865754000864527e-08)


Normality test for pressure for machine 1
NormaltestResult(statistic=238.38331828215757, pvalue=1.720759382097052e-52)


Normality test for vibration for machine 1
NormaltestResult(statistic=256.5133753274386, pvalue=1.9898863846130465e-56)

Since all of the p-values are less than the significance level of 0.05, we can conclude that all of them do not follow a normal distribution. The results provide strong evidence against the assumption of normality

Observation¶

  • It looks like it is a synthetic dataset, so there are no missing values. But we can see that the data is not entirely clean. There are a few spikes in the data that are likely due to sensor malfunction.
  • There are 100 machines in this dataset.
  • There are no duplicate rows in the dataset.
  • Volt, rotate, pressure, and vibration all do not have a normal distribution, but there are some outliers in the data.

Maintenance Data¶

The dataset includes records of component replacements, which are captured in the maintenance table. Components are replaced in two scenarios:

Proactive Maintenance: During the regular scheduled visits, technicians proactively replace components as part of preventive maintenance measures. These replacements are logged in the dataset, indicating planned maintenance actions.

Reactive Maintenance: In cases where a component experiences a breakdown, technicians perform unscheduled maintenance to replace the faulty component. These instances are considered failures, and the corresponding data is recorded under the failures table.

The maintenance data contains records both from 2014 and 2015.

Lets checks if there is the same failure for the same machine within 2 days¶

In [ ]:
def check_failure_within_2_days(df):
    # sort the data frame by machine ID and datetime
    df = df.sort_values(["machineID", "datetime"])

    # create a column for previous datetime
    df["previous_datetime"] = df.groupby(["machineID"])["datetime"].shift(1)

    # create a column for previous failure
    df["previous_failure"] = df.groupby(["machineID"])["failure"].shift(1)

    # create a column for days between failures
    df["days_between_failure"] = (df["datetime"] - df["previous_datetime"]).dt.days

    # create a column for failure within 7 days
    df["failure_within_2_days"] = (df["days_between_failure"] <= 2) & (
        df["failure"] == df["previous_failure"]
    )

    # drop the columns which are not needed
    df = df.drop(
        ["previous_datetime", "previous_failure", "days_between_failure"], axis=1
    )

    return df


df_failures = check_failure_within_2_days(df_failures)
